Guest: And so that's the cosmic microwave background radiation.

221
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:05,739
Guest: If you if you've still got a TV with an antenna and you turn it to a dead channel, which I guess would be all of them.

222
00:12:05,779 --> 00:12:16,120
Guest: now, and you turn the brightness way down, that about one percent of the little white specks that will show up on your screen come from the cosmic microwave background radiation.

223
00:12:16,620 --> 00:12:18,960
Scott: I don't think you're using a TV, though, for your research, right?

224
00:12:19,680 --> 00:12:22,797
Scott: You're using some kind of fancy telescope or satellite or something?

225
00:12:23,380 --> 00:12:24,760
Guest: Yeah, TVs are how you find poltergeists.

226
00:12:28,660 --> 00:12:30,119
Guest: Again, astrophysics, not astrology.

227
00:12:32,741 --> 00:12:35,100
Guest: So, yeah, I'm not an observational cosmologist.

228
00:12:35,861 --> 00:12:39,160
Guest: I'm a computational cosmologist, so I don't look through telescopes.

229
00:12:39,480 --> 00:12:42,660
Guest: I don't build telescopes or satellites to collect data.

230
00:12:43,803 --> 00:12:46,420
Guest: I take the data and I crunch it with a computer.

231
00:12:47,080 --> 00:12:53,060
Guest: So the instrument that I use the most often, aside from, you know, pencil and paper, is a MacBook Pro.

232
00:12:53,900 --> 00:13:10,700
Guest: But the the stuff that we use to collect the data these days is usually, well, for the cosmic microwave background radiation, our best data comes either from satellites that are way out in space and not even orbiting Earth.

233
00:13:11,380 --> 00:13:21,780
Guest: They're out at what's called a Lagrange point, so they don't get interference from Earth and they take full sky pictures in the microwave range.

234
00:13:24,782 --> 00:13:29,660
Guest: Or from ground-based surveys from, you know, really well-situated telescopes.

235
00:13:29,780 --> 00:13:36,000
Guest: Like, there's a nice telescope at the South Pole that is taking really detailed pictures of the cosmic microwave background radiation.

236
00:13:36,562 --> 00:13:40,220
Guest: But the thing is, you can't get a full sky picture from the ground.

237
00:13:41,129 --> 00:13:41,439
Scott: That's true.

238
00:13:41,880 --> 00:13:44,935
Guest: And that's not so good.

239
00:13:44,995 --> 00:13:46,100
Guest: We need full sky pictures.

240
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:50,760
Guest: We also need really detailed pictures of the sort that you can only get from the ground, so we need both.

241
00:13:52,282 --> 00:13:54,578
Guest: So I take that data and crunch it.

242
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:57,853
Rym: So what kind of software, like what kind of tool would you use to crunch?

243
00:13:57,873 --> 00:13:59,220
Rym: I mean, how much data even is that?

244
00:13:59,945 --> 00:14:00,396
Guest: It's a lot.

245
00:14:01,960 --> 00:14:04,320
Scott: Does it take a long time to download from the satellite in space?

246
00:14:05,181 --> 00:14:07,371
Guest: I don't know how long it takes to download from the satellite in space.

247
00:14:07,432 --> 00:14:09,200
Guest: I mostly download it from websites.

248
00:14:09,261 --> 00:14:10,079
Guest: That's a good idea.

249
00:14:11,242 --> 00:14:13,040
Guest: They've already downloaded it from the satellite.

250
00:14:13,621 --> 00:14:17,079
Guest: So, yeah, I don't know what the bandwidth of the connection out to a Lagrange point is.

251
00:14:17,761 --> 00:14:29,520
Guest: But, yeah, basically, yeah, I get this data, and there are some pre-existing software packages that will crunch it for me somewhat.

252
00:14:32,664 --> 00:14:35,960
Guest: There's something called HealPix, which this is getting real technical.

253
00:14:36,083 --> 00:14:36,839
Scott: How do you spell that?

254
00:14:37,961 --> 00:14:40,480
Guest: H-E-A-L-P-I-X, HealPix.

255
00:14:41,200 --> 00:14:45,440
Guest: So, yeah, HealPix is basically a package for crunching this data.

256
00:14:48,342 --> 00:14:49,906
Guest: But it will only crunch it so far.

257
00:14:49,946 --> 00:14:55,120
Guest: It basically lets you display the data, and it also lets you do various simple transformations on it.

258
00:14:55,140 --> 00:15:05,220
Guest: It's also a format for taking the entire sky and basically pixelating it, because, you know, you've got something that's not flat.

259
00:15:05,841 --> 00:15:10,056
Guest: Now you need to display it as a set of pixels and deal with it.

260
00:15:10,136 --> 00:15:11,039
Guest: So how are you going to do that?

261
00:15:12,063 --> 00:15:12,734
Guest: So there's that.

262
00:15:15,421 --> 00:15:18,460
Guest: But then a lot of what I end up doing is writing code to do further analysis.

263
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:24,000
Guest: Because, you know, something like HealPix or some other software package that someone else wrote will only take you so far.

264
00:15:24,200 --> 00:15:24,934
Guest: If I want to do...

265
00:15:25,281 --> 00:15:27,060
Scott: And it's also work that someone's already done.

266
00:15:27,500 --> 00:15:31,900
Scott: So running the data through the same software someone else already wrote is going to get you the answer someone else has already found.

267
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:32,766
Guest: Essentially, yeah.

268
00:15:32,846 --> 00:15:34,540
Guest: So I want to do something fundamentally new.

269
00:15:34,720 --> 00:15:42,420
Guest: That means I have to, at the very least, take the results of that other person's software package and run it through my own software, which is a lot of what I do.

270
00:15:42,680 --> 00:15:44,800
Guest: So I write a lot of Python code.

271
00:15:45,062 --> 00:15:46,480
Scott: I also write a lot of Python code.

272
00:15:46,601 --> 00:15:49,340
Scott: Yeah, Python code is... Much easier to write for me than for you.

273
00:15:49,620 --> 00:15:54,700
Guest: Well, you know, there are some Python packages like NumPy and SciPy that make it a lot easier.

274
00:15:54,800 --> 00:16:00,560
Guest: And then when you want to actually write a paper, there's Matplotlib, which helps a lot as well.

275
00:16:01,384 --> 00:16:04,620
Guest: So, yeah, I write a lot of Python code.

276
00:16:05,180 --> 00:16:14,660
Guest: And then I sometimes have to edit other people's C code, or on really bad days I have to edit other people's Fortran code, which is my least favorite thing in the world.

277
00:16:15,941 --> 00:16:24,420
Guest: Yeah, there's a software package that's written entirely in Fortran and has almost no comments, but it's also the best package of its kind.

278
00:16:24,841 --> 00:16:30,560
Guest: And sometimes it's easier to sort of modify that package rather than try to replicate it myself.

279
00:16:31,080 --> 00:16:36,820
Scott: See, in cases like that, I always wonder, like, somebody could just go in and, like, line by line translate it to, like, some other language, you know?

280
00:16:37,180 --> 00:16:43,696
Scott: Even if it's like, you know, Fortran's not object-oriented, but it's like, you know, you can write non-object-oriented Python, right?

281
00:16:43,777 --> 00:16:44,859
Scott: You can just go through...

282
00:16:45,200 --> 00:16:50,280
Guest: Well, actually, frighteningly, there is a way to do object-oriented Fortran, and I wish I didn't know that.

283
00:16:51,100 --> 00:16:52,096
Guest: I did not know that.

284
00:16:55,680 --> 00:17:04,760
Guest: But, yeah, you could do that if you had a lot of time and nothing better to do, which I can't imagine anyone in the world is ever in that situation.

285
00:17:04,820 --> 00:17:06,960
Rym: Scott, that's the thing that some people might do or believe.

286
00:17:07,320 --> 00:17:07,999
Scott: There are people.

287
00:17:08,480 --> 00:17:10,440
Guest: Yeah, I suppose that's true.

288
00:17:10,619 --> 00:17:13,025
Rym: So what kinds of things do you look for?

289
00:17:13,065 --> 00:17:20,599
Rym: Like, what's something you recently, you know, you're crunching this data, and we're talking in very high levels right now, but, like, what's the kind of thing you're actually looking for or trying to find?

290
00:17:20,964 --> 00:17:21,796
Guest: Well, okay, so...

291
00:17:22,079 --> 00:17:23,680
Rym: Or trying to prove, or whatever it is you're going for.

292
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:36,320
Guest: Yeah, so going back to that one-sentence description of, you know, I look for stuff in the universe right now to try to figure out what the universe looked like right after the Big Bang.

293
00:17:37,580 --> 00:17:43,880
Guest: Specifically, the stuff I end up looking for, it's not like I'm looking for a particular galaxy cluster.

294
00:17:44,682 --> 00:17:49,272
Guest: The laws that govern the universe at this level are mostly statistical.

295
00:17:49,994 --> 00:17:52,540
Guest: So what I end up looking for are statistical quantities.

296
00:17:55,281 --> 00:18:04,342
Guest: So, specifically, what I've been looking for lately, and now I guess this gets slightly technical, there's a question... Yeah, okay, fine.

297
00:18:05,205 --> 00:18:10,964
Guest: So there's the question of how... You know what?

298
00:18:11,327 --> 00:18:12,820
Guest: No, I'm going to back up for a second.

299
00:18:16,471 --> 00:18:23,030
Guest: The theory of general relativity from Albert Einstein describes the universe on the very largest scales.

300
00:18:24,570 --> 00:18:28,910
Guest: And it also just tells us how gravity works on smaller scales, but we can use it to describe the universe on largest scales.

301
00:18:31,951 --> 00:18:45,350
Guest: And there's a set of equations that go along with general relativity, and you can sort of basically put in the universe that you have, or put in certain conditions about the universe, and those equations will pop out a solution, which describes where you live.

302
00:18:46,090 --> 00:18:57,010
Guest: And to describe the universe on the very largest scales, we usually punch into those equations the assumptions that the universe is what's called isotropic and homogeneous.

303
00:18:57,210 --> 00:18:59,899
Guest: So it looks the same in all directions everywhere.

304
00:19:00,862 --> 00:19:03,530
Guest: And on very large scales, this is an extremely good assumption.

305
00:19:03,650 --> 00:19:08,224
Guest: If you take a picture of the universe on really large scales, it's kind of smooth.

306
00:19:09,146 --> 00:19:10,430
Guest: The universe looks the same everywhere.

307
00:19:11,052 --> 00:19:15,768
Guest: The problem is, that's certainly not true at small scales, otherwise we wouldn't be here.

308
00:19:16,730 --> 00:19:19,585
Guest: And remember, I said the universe is pretty sparsely populated.

309
00:19:19,605 --> 00:19:20,570
Guest: Well, not here.

310
00:19:21,531 --> 00:19:25,850
Guest: We have a lot more atoms here per cubic meter than you do out in intergalactic space.

311
00:19:26,190 --> 00:19:33,610
Rym: So in any given direction, the cosmic background radiation is uniform, but then close up, there's a galaxy here and there isn't one mirrored on the other side.

312
00:19:33,730 --> 00:19:34,191
Guest: Exactly.

313
00:19:34,292 --> 00:19:39,845
Guest: And even the cosmic microwave background radiation, it's not actually uniform in all directions.

314
00:19:40,026 --> 00:19:41,650
Guest: It has tiny little variations.

315
00:19:42,670 --> 00:19:46,563
Guest: And so that's interesting, because the variations we have now are not tiny.

316
00:19:46,924 --> 00:19:48,590
Guest: The variations we have now are huge.

317
00:19:49,972 --> 00:19:52,939
Guest: It's not a fraction of an atom per cubic meter here.

318
00:19:53,380 --> 00:19:57,230
Guest: It's something like 10 to the 23 or more atoms per cubic meter here.

319
00:19:57,711 --> 00:20:06,590
Guest: Whereas if you go and look at the cosmic microwave background radiation, you see differences, but those differences are like one part in 10,000.

320
00:20:06,590 --> 00:20:10,479
Scott: But is that one part in 10,000, like an echo of?

321
00:20:10,740 --> 00:20:11,000
Scott: back?

322
00:20:11,061 --> 00:20:15,070
Scott: then there was a huge lump in a place which causes a very small lump now?

323
00:20:15,811 --> 00:20:17,697
Scott: How does it correlate?

324
00:20:17,717 --> 00:20:21,710
Scott: Like if you see that in the background radiation now, what does that tell you about what was there then?

325
00:20:22,131 --> 00:20:32,531
Guest: It tells you that what was there then was a piece of the universe that was slightly more or less lumpy to the tune of one part in about 100,000.

326
00:20:32,531 --> 00:20:34,895
Guest: The relationship is proportional.

327
00:20:35,516 --> 00:20:42,530
Guest: So the question is, how do we get from these tiny little lumps to the incredibly lumpy universe we live in now?

328
00:20:43,171 --> 00:20:45,513
Guest: The answer to that turns out to be pretty easy to understand.

329
00:20:45,573 --> 00:20:46,454
Guest: It's just gravity.

330
00:20:47,254 --> 00:21:03,930
Guest: If you just throw gravity into a slightly lumpy universe and let that universe evolve for 13.8 billion years, what's going to happen is the slightly denser places will attract more matter, and the slightly less dense places will have matter fall away from them.

331
00:21:04,730 --> 00:21:10,130
Guest: And eventually, after a few billion years, you end up with stars, galaxies, galaxy clusters.

332
00:21:10,512 --> 00:21:12,099
Rym: Alright, but that puts us to an earlier order.

333
00:21:12,139 --> 00:21:12,561
Rym: question then.

334
00:21:12,641 --> 00:21:14,490
Rym: Where did that original slight lumpiness come from?

335
00:21:14,671 --> 00:21:15,470
Guest: And that's exactly it.

336
00:21:15,470 --> 00:21:20,688
Scott: Well, I mean, is it a false assumption that it was originally perfectly smooth, or was there, you know...

337
00:21:21,771 --> 00:21:23,290
Guest: Well, so those are active research questions.

338
00:21:23,374 --> 00:21:23,650
Guest: Alright.

339
00:21:23,850 --> 00:21:24,870
Guest: That's essentially where I work on them.

340
00:21:24,930 --> 00:21:26,830
Rym: Man, you scientists never have any answers.

341
00:21:27,330 --> 00:21:31,450
Guest: Well, I mean, so we have, actually the real problem is we have too many and we don't know which one's right.

342
00:21:32,133 --> 00:21:36,610
Guest: We have many, many, many, many, many different theories about where there's too many differences came from.

343
00:21:36,610 --> 00:21:44,370
Scott: What are like, you know, three or four, you know, a few of the big ones that are getting a lot of, that people seem to think are right and aren't crazy kooks?

344
00:21:44,751 --> 00:21:45,854
Guest: So there's one big one.

345
00:21:45,875 --> 00:21:47,099
Guest: There's one really big one.

346
00:21:47,721 --> 00:21:50,410
Guest: And this is something called inflation.

347
00:21:51,070 --> 00:21:51,207
Scott: Okay.

348
00:21:52,311 --> 00:22:04,970
Guest: And the basic idea is, okay, in the very early universe, the very, very early universe, a fraction of a fraction of a second, a billionth of a billionth of a billionth of a second after the Big Bang.

349
00:22:07,891 --> 00:22:14,640
Guest: There was a brief period where the universe expanded very, very rapidly.

350
00:22:16,222 --> 00:22:20,528
Guest: You know, expanded something like 10 to the 50 times.

351
00:22:23,070 --> 00:22:27,685
Guest: So it expanded by a factor of a one with 50 zeros after it.

352
00:22:28,708 --> 00:22:29,330
Guest: Something like that.

353
00:22:29,930 --> 00:22:35,730
Guest: So, sorry, it might be a one with 20 zeros after it, but it doesn't really matter.

354
00:22:37,373 --> 00:22:40,169
Scott: The point is, is that there are a lot of zeros in less than a second.

355
00:22:40,410 --> 00:22:42,196
Guest: Yeah, a hell of a lot of zeros, yeah.

356
00:22:42,236 --> 00:22:47,150
Guest: So the point is, for a very, very brief fraction of a second, the universe expanded a hell of a lot and then that stopped.

357
00:22:47,230 --> 00:22:49,890
Guest: And it continued to expand after that, just not nearly as quickly.

358
00:22:51,171 --> 00:22:59,450
Guest: So the interesting thing here is what that would do, I mean, that does a lot of things and solves a lot of problems and brings up other problems.

359
00:22:59,530 --> 00:23:11,330
Guest: But what that does for this question of where did the original tiny limpiness come from is it says, OK, well, quantum mechanics is the set of rules that govern the universe on really tiny scales.

360
00:23:12,251 --> 00:23:15,577
Guest: And quantum mechanics says that sometimes crap just happens.

361
00:23:16,238 --> 00:23:19,003
Guest: Quantum mechanics is what we call fundamentally stochastic.

362
00:23:19,124 --> 00:23:22,430
Guest: There's randomness in the universe at a very low level.

363
00:23:22,831 --> 00:23:29,350
Guest: So if we were looking at something really tiny and we saw tiny differences all over the place, we'd say, well, we don't really need an explanation for that.

364
00:23:30,391 --> 00:23:33,110
Guest: That can be explained just by the nature of quantum mechanics.

365
00:23:34,170 --> 00:23:51,910
Guest: So what inflation says is, OK, yeah, so there are these tiny differences, but then the universe expanded so rapidly that those tiny differences got expanded up and turned into tiny differences on a macroscopic scale, on a scale bigger than the scales that quantum mechanics really deals with.

366
00:23:52,672 --> 00:23:54,416
Guest: And so they kind of got frozen in.

367
00:23:55,218 --> 00:23:59,109
Guest: So basically, and this is this is a direct quote from.

368
00:24:01,771 --> 00:24:11,750
Guest: Now I'm going to forget someone famous said that basically these tiny little differences in the cosmic microwave background radiation are quantum mechanics writ large on the sky.

369
00:24:13,130 --> 00:24:16,117
Guest: So that is that is a very popular theory inflation.

370
00:24:16,238 --> 00:24:17,501
Guest: for explaining this.

371
00:24:17,561 --> 00:24:21,230
Guest: There is one problem, which is, well, two problems.

372
00:24:21,290 --> 00:24:25,985
Guest: The first is what drove that period of rapid inflation?

373
00:24:26,828 --> 00:24:27,450
Guest: And second.

374
00:24:30,570 --> 00:24:31,593
Guest: Which inflation?

375
00:24:31,613 --> 00:24:38,590
Guest: Because it turns out that if you try to answer the first question, you can answer it in dozens and dozens and dozens of different ways.

376
00:24:39,951 --> 00:24:56,010
Guest: And that's that it's difficult to distinguish between those different theories of inflation, because we're talking about a period in the universe's history that is not only before the oldest light, but also before the oldest atoms.

377
00:24:56,631 --> 00:25:03,010
Guest: Atomic nuclei were formed in in the universe between three and 20 minutes after the Big Bang.

378
00:25:04,291 --> 00:25:12,310
Guest: So it's it's older than anything that has survived until the current time, except for those tiny fluctuations themselves.

379
00:25:13,170 --> 00:25:28,030
Guest: So by studying the way stuff is arranged in the universe right now, we can learn more about the distribution of those tiny fluctuations and thereby hopefully learn more about what kind of inflation happened or if inflation happened at all.

380
00:25:28,311 --> 00:25:29,318
Scott: This is a joke for him.

381
00:25:29,439 --> 00:25:31,110
Scott: It's the darkness that came before.

382
00:25:33,192 --> 00:25:33,715
Guest: I have no idea.

383
00:25:33,796 --> 00:25:35,103
Scott: I know you're not supposed to get that joke.

384
00:25:35,284 --> 00:25:35,767
Guest: It's OK.

385
00:25:35,807 --> 00:25:36,109
Scott: That's OK.

386
00:25:36,650 --> 00:25:49,330
Rym: We argue a lot about the nature of, well, not necessarily free will, but causality in the sense that if I mean, you're basically what you've said from this theory is that quantum mechanics effectively, if you zoom in far enough, things are random.

387
00:25:49,450 --> 00:25:50,434
Rym: We don't know or care why.

388
00:25:51,337 --> 00:25:54,730
Rym: Or if we do care, that's a separate field of inquiry.

389
00:25:55,032 --> 00:25:57,969
Guest: I think the second one is where I'm going to go with that, because I care very much.

390
00:25:58,850 --> 00:25:59,888
Guest: Other people may not.

391
00:26:01,850 --> 00:26:08,288
Rym: But that is a question that for the intent, the purpose of discussion, most scientists will say when talking about these other things, we don't know why.

392
00:26:08,408 --> 00:26:09,070
Rym: And that's separate.

393
00:26:09,732 --> 00:26:10,538
Guest: Yes, that is it is.

394
00:26:10,558 --> 00:26:12,210
Guest: We don't you know, it is separate.

395
00:26:12,650 --> 00:26:13,961
Guest: Some people say that we do know why.

396
00:26:13,981 --> 00:26:15,050
Guest: Other people say that we don't.

397
00:26:15,290 --> 00:26:20,350
Guest: There's a whole field called Foundations of Quantum Mechanics, which deals with this kind of thing, but it's not relevant.

398
00:26:20,450 --> 00:26:28,830
Rym: So we imply that on the macro scale, that things happen in a deterministic fashion in the sense that we can predict, you know, gravity and all these things.

399
00:26:28,930 --> 00:26:35,590
Rym: We could theoretically predict how macro bodies will react to events and they'll always react to the exact same event in the exact same way.

400
00:26:36,750 --> 00:26:37,431
Guest: Kind of.

401
00:26:37,712 --> 00:26:41,838
Rym: Or is it that they won't because we can't perfectly recreate?

402
00:26:42,139 --> 00:26:48,890
Rym: or is it that they won't because those tiny fluctuations we're ignoring actually make it impossible for the same thing to happen twice?

403
00:26:51,490 --> 00:26:54,905
Guest: So, yes, is essentially the answer to your question.

404
00:26:54,925 --> 00:26:55,829
Guest: Let me give you.

405
00:26:56,371 --> 00:26:57,730
Scott: He's trying to ask philosophy questions.

406
00:26:57,991 --> 00:26:59,750
Guest: Yeah, no, asking philosophy questions is fine.

407
00:27:00,030 --> 00:27:02,050
Rym: No, but in a very direct, I only want the physics answer.

408
00:27:02,330 --> 00:27:07,150
Guest: OK, well, so first of all, to toot my own horn a little bit more, I actually do have a degree in philosophy.

409
00:27:07,570 --> 00:27:08,401
Guest: Oh, fancy.

410
00:27:09,350 --> 00:27:09,948
Guest: No, I did my undergrad.

411
00:27:10,210 --> 00:27:11,610
Scott: He's got a whole bucket full of horns.

412
00:27:11,811 --> 00:27:12,213
Scott: It's true.

