00:39:14,320 --> 00:39:14,650
Guest: Precisely.

640
00:39:14,774 --> 00:39:14,959
Guest: Yeah.

641
00:39:15,120 --> 00:39:25,860
Guest: So gravity, as a result, governs a lot of what we see in the universe on large scales and also a lot of what we see on these sort of intermediate scales where we live, simply because we're living on a big thing.

642
00:39:27,081 --> 00:39:31,600
Guest: But if you want a demonstration of gravity being really weak, you've got that whiteboard over there with magnets on it.

643
00:39:31,720 --> 00:39:41,220
Guest: So those tiny magnets are being held up by magnetism, OK, against the entire gravitational pull of the Earth.

644
00:39:42,421 --> 00:39:54,840
Guest: So those really, really small magnets and those magnets aren't even using sort of the full strength of electromagnetism because there's pretty weak magnets and they're also shitty ones that fall off the fridge.

645
00:39:54,860 --> 00:39:56,103
Guest: They're also dipoles.

646
00:39:56,143 --> 00:39:57,786
Guest: They've got both a north and south pole.

647
00:39:57,846 --> 00:40:04,220
Guest: This means that they're not actually going to be as strong as if you had, say, a positive and negative electric charge.

648
00:40:06,461 --> 00:40:14,040
Guest: I mean, you could levitate a building pretty easily if you put a bunch of positive charges on the floor and a bunch of positive charges on the building.

649
00:40:14,600 --> 00:40:15,869
Guest: I mean, it would then fall over.

650
00:40:15,950 --> 00:40:17,259
Guest: It's not going to be stable that way.

651
00:40:17,400 --> 00:40:18,178
Rym: So it's a big pencil again.

652
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:19,083
Guest: Yeah, exactly.

653
00:40:19,143 --> 00:40:19,404
Guest: Yes.

654
00:40:19,525 --> 00:40:22,740
Guest: But nonetheless, it's really easy to counteract gravity with any of the other forces.

655
00:40:23,700 --> 00:40:24,524
Guest: But yeah, gravity, why?

656
00:40:25,388 --> 00:40:27,559
Guest: gravity is sort of messed up and doesn't fit in.

657
00:40:29,041 --> 00:40:33,680
Guest: The best analogy I ever heard about this is basically the standard model tells you how the players act on the stage.

658
00:40:34,001 --> 00:40:37,379
Guest: The problem with gravity is gravity comes in and warps the stage.

659
00:40:38,340 --> 00:40:47,720
Guest: Gravity is a set of rules for how the stage behaves, not the players, because gravity, as general relativity tells us, is a warping of space time.

660
00:40:49,160 --> 00:40:50,184
Guest: So, yeah.

661
00:40:50,364 --> 00:40:54,960
Guest: So we knew that the standard model wasn't complete.

662
00:40:55,440 --> 00:40:58,859
Guest: And since then, we've discovered several things that don't fit in with the standard model.

663
00:41:00,740 --> 00:41:02,639
Guest: Three other things, like I said, four things total.

664
00:41:04,245 --> 00:41:05,990
Guest: One of those things is dark matter.

665
00:41:06,712 --> 00:41:09,080
Guest: There is nothing in the standard model that can account for dark matter.

666
00:41:10,221 --> 00:41:17,820
Guest: And another thing is dark energy, which is causing the expansion of the universe to accelerate rather than slow down over time.

667
00:41:18,720 --> 00:41:23,680
Guest: And this has we don't know as much about dark energy as we know about dark matter.

668
00:41:24,642 --> 00:41:31,059
Guest: But assuming that I mean, assuming that we're not just wrong about gravity, something is causing this.

669
00:41:32,462 --> 00:41:34,779
Guest: And there's nothing for that in the standard model either.

670
00:41:35,662 --> 00:41:38,400
Guest: And then there's the last thing is this thing called neutrino oscillation.

671
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:47,200
Guest: Basically, the standard model says that neutrinos shouldn't have mass, but we know that we now have evidence that neutrinos do have mass.

672
00:41:48,361 --> 00:41:53,199
Guest: And it's a small mass, very small, but the standard model can't account for that.

673
00:41:53,880 --> 00:41:59,420
Guest: So these four things, gravity, dark energy, dark matter, neutrino oscillation, they don't fit in the standard model.

674
00:42:00,061 --> 00:42:07,640
Guest: And even if you're skeptical about dark energy and you say no, dark energy is just that we don't understand how gravity works on really big scales, the other three are pretty solid.

675
00:42:08,440 --> 00:42:10,259
Guest: And certainly we know that gravity is real.

676
00:42:11,860 --> 00:42:17,059
Guest: And we've seen neutrino oscillation in the lab, and the evidence for dark matter is pretty good too.

677
00:42:17,500 --> 00:42:21,020
Guest: So none of those are explained by the standard model.

678
00:42:21,642 --> 00:42:33,480
Guest: If we can come up with something that breaks the standard model, if we see some evidence in a particle accelerator of something that is not accounted for by the standard model, that would give us hints of the next theory.

679
00:42:33,980 --> 00:42:42,080
Guest: And that next theory could account for dark matter and dark energy, which are two of the biggest outstanding questions in cosmology.

680
00:42:42,340 --> 00:42:45,040
Guest: And so this is a connection between particle physics and cosmology.

